\textbf{Dataset:} We use data from the Shared Task on Patient-Centric Clinical Dialogue Summarization. The corpus comprises train/validation/test splits of carefully annotated clinical encounters. The dialogues exhibit high linguistic complexity: lengths vary dramatically (ranging from 4,000 to over 7,000 tokens per encounter), and natural code-switching with English medical terminology is highly prevalent across all regional languages. 

For all generations, we utilize greedy decoding (temperature $\tau=0.1$, top-$p=0.95$) to minimize stochastic hallucinations, a standard practice for high-stakes clinical tasks. For the few-shot condition, the $k{=}1$ exemplar was randomly sampled from the language-specific training split to prevent selection bias.

